            id: 'adv-m1-l3', title: 'Mapping the Family System', type: 'exercise',
            content: 'Before you can advise a family, you need to understand its structure. This exercise, adapted from Jaffe\'s governance consulting methodology, gives you a diagnostic tool you\'ll use in every family enterprise engagement.\n\nExercise:\n\nStep 1: Draw the family genogram — who is related to whom, across at least three generations. Include marriages, divorces, and deaths. Note ages and generational positions.\n\nStep 2: Overlay the business roles — who works in the enterprise, at what level, and in what capacity? Who owns shares, and in what proportion? Who sits on the board or any governance body?\n\nStep 3: Map the influence lines — who has informal power? Who are the connectors (people everyone talks to)? Who are the gatekeepers (people who control access to information or decision-makers)? Who are the isolates (people who are disconnected)?\n\nStep 4: Identify the unspoken rules — what topics are off-limits? What decisions have been deferred for years? What alliances and rifts exist below the surface? Where is triangulation happening?\n\nStep 5: Locate the presenting problem in the system. The issue the family called you about is rarely the real issue. Use your system map to hypothesize where the deeper dynamics are. A "strategy disagreement" may actually be a succession conflict. A "governance problem" may actually be a trust deficit between siblings.\n\nThis map should be updated regularly throughout any engagement. The family system is dynamic — and your understanding of it should be too.'
