            id: 'adv-m2-l2', title: 'Predictable Crisis Points', type: 'learn',
            content: 'Ward\'s decades of research identified the predictable crises that family enterprises face at each transition. As an advisor, knowing these in advance is your most valuable diagnostic tool.\n\nThe Founder\'s Trap (1st generation): The business can\'t grow beyond the founder\'s personal capacity. Everything flows through one person. The founder can\'t delegate because "no one does it as well as I do." Advisors must help the founder build systems and develop people — not just grow the business.\n\nThe Sibling Rivalry Crisis (2nd generation): When the founder leaves, siblings who were united by a parent\'s authority must now govern themselves. Old childhood dynamics resurface. Who leads? How are decisions made? What if one sibling works 80 hours and another doesn\'t work at all but owns equal shares? Advisors must help build governance structures before the crisis hits.\n\nThe Cousin Complexity Crisis (3rd generation): The family has grown. Some members know each other well; others are near strangers. Some are in the business; many are not. The emotional attachment to the enterprise varies widely. Advisors must help the family build institutional governance that works for a large, diverse ownership group.\n\nThe Relevance Crisis (any generation): The business model that made the family wealthy may no longer be viable. DeCiantis and Lansberg\'s "Enduring Enterprise" shows that the families who survive this crisis are the ones who can separate their identity from the original business — and reinvent the enterprise while preserving the family\'s purpose.'
