            content: 'Exercise: Apply the developmental model to a real or simulated client scenario.\n\nScenario: A second-generation family enterprise with three siblings as co-owners. One sibling serves as CEO. One manages a division. One is not involved in operations but draws a salary as a "consultant." The CEO wants to bring in professional management and reduce family involvement in daily operations. The non-operating sibling objects, fearing loss of income and influence. The division-managing sibling is caught in the middle.\n\nStep 1: Map the system. Using Gersick\'s model, identify the current stage of the business, ownership, and family dimensions.\n\nStep 2: Identify the real issue. Using the frameworks you\'ve learned, what\'s really driving this conflict? Map the positions (what each person says they want) and the interests (what they actually need).\n\nStep 3: Anticipate the next crisis. Based on the developmental model, what challenge is coming next? How should the family prepare?\n\nStep 4: Design your advisory approach. What governance structures would you recommend? What conversations need to happen? In what order? With whom in the room? Who should facilitate?\n\nStep 5: Identify your boundaries. Where does your expertise end? What other advisors should be in the ecosystem? How do you coordinate with legal counsel, financial advisors, and family therapists without stepping on each other\'s toes — or creating conflicting advice?\n\nWrite up your analysis in 1-2 pages. This is the kind of structured thinking that separates generalist advisors from family enterprise specialists.'
