            content: 'The Family Firm Institute\'s body of knowledge identifies three competency domains for family enterprise advisors: family dynamics, business systems, and governance/succession. The most effective advisors — and the ones families trust most deeply — are those who can integrate all three.\n\nThis integration looks different at each stage of an engagement:\n\nDiscovery Phase: Use systems thinking (Gersick\'s model) to understand the family\'s developmental stage. Map the system (Jaffe\'s genogram overlay). Identify the presenting issue and hypothesize the underlying dynamics (Bork\'s diagnostic approach).\n\nDesign Phase: Build governance structures (Keyt\'s layered framework) that address both the current needs and the one-generation-ahead requirements (Ward\'s principle). Incorporate conflict resolution mechanisms (McVeigh). Account for socioemotional wealth considerations (De Massis).\n\nFacilitation Phase: Structure conversations that enable the family to make their own decisions (McVeigh\'s facilitation framework). Create psychological safety (Sage-Hayward). Name the elephants (Bork). Build toward a shared dream (Lansberg).\n\nDevelopment Phase: Help the family invest in next-gen development (Begalla\'s credibility framework, Marchisio and Sage-Hayward\'s owner\'s mindset). Support knowledge transfer (Bork). Build human capital alongside financial capital (Hughes).\n\nSustainability Phase: Ensure governance becomes habit, not project (Schuman). Prepare for the next transition (Aronoff\'s lifelong succession model). Build enterprise resilience (DeCiantis). Step back when the family is ready to govern itself.\n\nEl Agamy adds a global perspective: these frameworks work across cultures and continents, but their application must be adapted to the specific cultural context of each family. The advisor who imposes a Western governance model on a Middle Eastern or Asian family enterprise without cultural adaptation will fail.'
